<section class="card">

<h2>How the Growing Season Works in {{ state.name }}</h2>

{% set season = state.season or null %}
{% set spring = season and season.frost and season.frost.spring or null %}
{% set fall = season and season.frost and season.frost.fall or null %}
{% set derived = season and season.derived or null %}
{% set gdd = season and season.gdd and season.gdd.remaining or null %}

{% set springStatus = spring and spring.status or null %}
{% set fallStatus = fall and fall.status or null %}
{% set frostFreeDays = derived and derived.frostFreeDays_p50 or null %}
{% set fallSpread = derived and derived.fallSpreadDays50 or null %}
{% set gddJul1 = gdd and gdd["07-01"] or null %}
{% set gddAug1 = gdd and gdd["08-01"] or null %}

{% if not season %}
  <p class="small">Season timing guidance isn’t available for this region yet.</p>

{% elif springStatus == "frost_free" or fallStatus == "frost_free" %}
  <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
    This region is typically frost-free in the normals dataset, so the growing season is less about beating a frost cutoff and more about managing heat, moisture, and crop maturity over time.
  </p>

{% else %}
  {% set seasonBand = "mid" %}
  {% if frostFreeDays %}
    {% if frostFreeDays <= 115 %}
      {% set seasonBand = "short" %}
    {% elif frostFreeDays >= 190 %}
      {% set seasonBand = "long" %}
    {% else %}
      {% set seasonBand = "mid" %}
    {% endif %}
  {% endif %}

  {% set runwayBand = "unknown" %}
  {% if gddJul1 is not null and gddAug1 is not null %}
    {% if gddJul1 >= 1700 and gddAug1 >= 900 %}
      {% set runwayBand = "high" %}
    {% elif gddJul1 <= 1000 or gddAug1 <= 300 %}
      {% set runwayBand = "low" %}
    {% else %}
      {% set runwayBand = "mid" %}
    {% endif %}
  {% endif %}

  {% if seasonBand == "short" and runwayBand == "high" %}
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
      {{ state.name }} usually has a short but usable warm-season window. The main challenge is not peak-summer heat, but getting crops established early enough to make full use of it before conditions tighten again.
    </p>
  {% elif seasonBand == "short" %}
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
      {{ state.name }} is a short-season growing environment. The season closes quickly enough that variety maturity, planting timing, and early establishment usually matter more than small differences in calendar timing.
    </p>
  {% elif seasonBand == "long" and runwayBand == "high" %}
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
      {{ state.name }} usually gives gardeners more flexibility. A longer season and stronger late-summer heat make staggered planting, second rounds, and longer-maturing crops more realistic than in colder interior regions.
    </p>
  {% elif seasonBand == "long" %}
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
      {{ state.name }} usually has a relatively forgiving season, but results still depend on how quickly gardens warm in spring and how well crop choices match local conditions.
    </p>
  {% else %}
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
      {{ state.name }} is mostly a timing-and-variety season. Reliable results usually come from planting on time, matching maturity to the frost window, and making good use of the remaining summer heat.
    </p>
  {% endif %}

  <ul class="small" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
    {% if seasonBand == "short" %}
      <li><strong>Warm-season crops:</strong> usually perform best when they are established promptly after the last spring frost.</li>
      <li><strong>Variety maturity matters:</strong> shorter-season cultivars are often the safer choice than longer-season bets.</li>
      <li><strong>Protection can help:</strong> row cover, transplants, and sheltered spots often improve consistency in a short season.</li>
    {% elif seasonBand == "long" %}
      <li><strong>Stagger planting dates:</strong> spreading sowings and transplanting windows often works better than planting everything at once.</li>
      <li><strong>Fall planting is more realistic:</strong> many areas still have enough runway for a meaningful second round of faster crops.</li>
      <li><strong>Summer management becomes the limiter:</strong> water, fertility, and pest pressure often matter more than season length alone.</li>
    {% else %}
      <li><strong>Start on time:</strong> early establishment is often the biggest controllable factor for warm-season success.</li>
      <li><strong>Match crops to the window:</strong> dependable harvests usually come from realistic maturity timing, not optimistic timing.</li>
      <li><strong>Use late summer well:</strong> fast greens, roots, and compact crops are often the best fit for a second round.</li>
    {% endif %}
  </ul>

  {% if fallSpread %}
    {% if fallSpread >= 35 %}
      <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
        Microclimate note: frost timing varies widely across {{ state.name }}, so sheltered gardens, urban sites, and warmer exposures can behave very differently from colder open areas.
      </p>
    {% elif fallSpread <= 15 %}
      <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
        Microclimate note: frost timing is fairly consistent across much of {{ state.name }}, so regional averages are usually a solid starting point.
      </p>
    {% else %}
      <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
        Microclimate note: local conditions still matter here. Low spots, exposed sites, and higher elevations often cool faster than the regional median suggests.
      </p>
    {% endif %}
  {% endif %}

  {% if gddAug1 is not null %}
    {% if gddAug1 >= 800 %}
      <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
        Late-summer note: there is often still meaningful heat left around early August, so second plantings of faster crops can still be worthwhile.
      </p>
    {% elif gddAug1 <= 300 %}
      <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
        Late-summer note: by early August, the remaining heat often tightens quickly. Late plantings tend to work best when they are fast, cold-tolerant, or protected.
      </p>
    {% endif %}
  {% endif %}

{% endif %}

